{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a9409ce5-87fb-42b0-812e-4af4ac112690","content":"These are two separate C# 15 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n---\n\n**Case 1: `left && right` with `dynamic`**\n\nThe `&&` operator is syntactic sugar requiring **three** things on the same type: `operator &`, `operator true`, and `operator false`. Your static type `IFilter` has `true`/`false` but **no `operator &`**. Previously the compiler deferred this entirely to the dynamic runtime binder. C# 15 now validates the short-circuit operator pattern at compile time for the static operand, even when the other operand is `dynamic`.\n\n**Fix options:**\n- Add `static IFilter operator &(IFilter x, IFilter y)` to `IFilter`\n- Use the explicit `&` operator instead of `&&` if short-circuiting isn't needed\n- Cast `left` to a concrete type that defines all three operators\n\n---\n\n**Case 2: `ref readonly` lambda — CS0518**\n\n`CS0518` means *\"Predefined type 'X' is not defined or imported.\"* When the compiler synthesizes a delegate type for a `ref readonly`-returning lambda, it now emits a new attribute (e.g., `RequiresLocationAttribute` or similar) on the return type metadata. If your project's target framework references are mismatched — compiler upgraded to C# 15 but runtime/SDK references not fully aligned — the required BCL type is missing.\n\n**Fix options:**\n- Ensure your `TargetFramework` is set to `net11.0` **and** you're using the matching .NET 11 SDK (check `dotnet --version`)\n- If multi-targeting or using a custom ref assembly set, verify the runtime libraries include the required compiler-services attribute\n- As a workaround, use an explicit delegate type instead of relying on the compiler-synthesized one:\n  ```csharp\n  delegate ref readonly int RefReadOnlyFunc();\n  RefReadOnlyFunc fn = () => ref value;\n  ```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"026af1e8-c0d3-4d7c-80c2-9ead7bd6b112","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about two new compiler errors they're getting after upgrading to .NET 11 / C# 15. Let me analyze both cases.\n\n**Case 1: `DynamicOps.cs` - `left && right` with dynamic**\n\nThis involves the `&&` operator with a `dynamic` operand. In C# 15 / .NET 11, there was a breaking change related to how the compiler handles user-defined `true`/`false` operators in combination with `&&`/`||` (short-circuit operators) when one operand is `dynamic`.\n\nThe `&&` operator is a short-circuit operator that relies on `operator true`/`operator false` and `operator &`. When one operand is `dynamic`, the compiler needs to resolve these at compile time for the static operand. \n\nIn C# 15, the compiler now enforces that when using `&&` with a `dynamic` operand, the static type must have both `operator true`/`false` and `operator &` defined on the same type. The problem is that `IFilter` defines `operator true`/`false` as static interface members, but `operator &` is defined on `CompositeFilter` instead. Since `left` is typed as `IFilter`, the compiler can't find `operator &` on that interface, so the `&&` operation fails to resolve. The static type `IFilter` has `operator true`/`false` but lacks `operator &`, so the `&&` operator can't be resolved at compile time—previously this would defer to the dynamic runtime binder, but C# 15 now validates it upfront. For the second case with `ref readonly` lambdas, there's likely a change in how the compiler handles `ref readonly` return types on lambda expressions, possibly related to predefined type resolution. RequiresLocationAttribute` or similar attributes that are required for `ref readonly` on synthesized delegates in newer C# versions, and these might not be available if the framework references haven't been properly updated.\n\nFor the first case, this looks like a breaking change where the compiler no longer allows user-defined conditional logical operators when one operand is `dynamic` and the type doesn't have both `operator true`/`false` AND `operator &`/`operator |` defined. Since `IFilter` only has the former, the `&&` operator fails.\n\nFor the second case, anonymous lambdas with `ref readonly` returns now require specific runtime attributes that might be missing if the runtime references weren't updated alongside the compiler upgrade. be honest about my analysis. The `&&` operator requires both `operator &` and `operator true`/`operator false` to be defined, and it seems the newer compiler now enforces that the static operand's type fully satisfies this pattern at compile time, even when the other operand is `dynamic`. The fix would be to add the missing `operator &` to the interface, cast to a concrete type, or use `&` instead if short-circuiting isn't needed.\n\nFor Case 2, I'm still working through what the breaking change might be around the ref readonly syntax. or maybe C# 15 changed how `ref readonly` returns work on lambdas entirely, possibly requiring explicit delegate types instead of compiler synthesis. The CS0518 error suggests the compiler is referencing a predefined type that isn't available in the current assembly set, which could indicate a mismatch between what the new language feature expects and what the project is actually targeting.","outputTokens":2809,"requestId":"2833:239FAB:17E4C2B:1A8E2BF:6A02861B"},"id":"19e2c7eb-b158-4973-b74f-8a0d4b4c7088","timestamp":"2026-05-12T01:45:58.465Z","parentId":"6dc183a7-4392-484f-b5c1-d43631a4ac8d"}
